In LaTeX, automatic table of contents (ToC) generation is achieved using the `\tableofcontents` command and sectional unit markers. Here's a step-by-step example:

**Document (toc:autoGenerate.tex)**
```latex
\documentclass{book}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Trigger ToC generation

\section{Introduction}
\label/secIntro % optional, for referencing purposes

\part{Part I — Theory}
\section{LaTeX Foundations}
\subsection{ToC Automation Basics}

\section{Appendix}
\subsection{Examples Summary}
\backmatter % finalize part inclusion (optional, but good practice)

\end{document}
```
**Explanation:**

1. Include essential packages (none required except `book` class, implicit functionality): Your setup is correct with `document class book`.
2. `\tableofcontents`: Place it at a visible point (usually after `\begin{document}`) to generate the ToC. LaTeX will traverse all subsequent sectional units and extract metadata.
3. Sectioning commands (e.g., \part, \section, \subsection): These markers provide the content titles and timestamps for the ToC entries.

When you compile this document (e.g., `pdflatex autoGenerate.tex`), LaTeX will generate a table of contents containing all the specified sectional units. The ToC will be automatically populated with headings and pages numbers.

Tip: For proper linking (if needed) and PDF navigation, consider adding `\label` wherever necessary, like in `\label/secIntro`.

